see if you can find remnants of the styloid     processes (L) of the temporal bones posterolateral to the entrance of the carotid canals. These long, thin projections of the temporal bone, give attachment to certain muscles and ligaments, but are frequently broken off from the skulls. Posterior to the styloid processes and medial to the mastoid process, identify the stylomastoid foramen (M), the site where the part of the facial nerve responsible for innervating the muscles of facial expression exits from the skull. Finally, locate the mandibular fossa (N), which articulates with the head of the condyloid process of the mandible to form the temporomandibular joint.
